he link to consumer behaviour. o The SwAM to support initiatives which pro- mote, organise and perform beach cleaning in areas particularly affected. 158 ibid National marine plastic litter policies in EU Member States: an overview ANNEX II: EU Countries Factsheets on marine litter related policies 61 United Kingdom 1. Are there any targets/strategies/policies at nation- al level that specifically address marine litter? \u2022\ufffd During the UN Ocean Conference in New York (5-9 June 2017), the United Kingdom (UK) has committed to do the following actions on Marine Litter159: o Adoption of the National Litter Strategy. o 5 pence charge for all single-use plastic carrier bags introduced. o Signup to the UN Clean Seas initiative. o Outcome of UK consultation on proposed ban on microbeads in cosmetics and per- sonal care products. \u2022\ufffd The UK has published a number of national strategies for marine litter: o National Litter Strategy for England in which marine litter is included160. o Scotland\u2019s 2014 Marine Litter Strategy161. o Northern Ireland\u2019s 2013 Marine Litter Strat- egy162. \u2022\ufffd The UK Marine Strategy Part Three sets out the legal framework relevant to address the issue of marine litter at UK level under the EU Marine Strategy Framework Directive (MSFD).163 The strategy includes the following targets: o An overall target: \u201cThe amount of litter, and its degradation products, on coastlines and in the marine environment are reducing over time and levels do not pose a significant risk to the coastal and marine environment, either as a result of direct mortality such as through entanglement, or by way of indirect impacts such as reduced fecundity or bio- accumulation of contaminants within food chains.\u201d o More specific targets: \u2022\ufffd Overall reduction in the number of visible litter items within specific categories/types on coastlines. \u2022\ufffd Surveillance indicator to monitor the quantities of litter on the seafloor. 159 https://oceanconference.un.org/commitments/?id=19719 160 HM Government, Litter Strategy for England April 2017 161 The Scottish Government, Marine Scotland: A Marine Litter Strategy for Scotland (2014) 162 Department of the Environment, Northern Ireland Marine Litter Strategy (2013) 163 Department for Environment, Food & Rural Affairs (Defra), Marine Strategy Part Three: UK programme of measures (2015) \u2022\ufffd Surveillance indicator to monitor the amounts of plastic found in the contents of fulmars stomachs as a method of determining litter floating at the surface (in line with OSPAR Ecological Quality Objective). \u2022\ufffd As a contracting party, the UK includes in its Marine Strategy the OSPAR Regional Action Plan on Marine Litter (RAP) in the list of measures taken to reduce the amount of litter in the marine environment. \u2022\ufffd The UK Marine Strategy also states the following policies that are relevant to address the issue of marine litter from a general and overarching perspective (e.g. littering as a criminal offence): o Environmental Protection Act 1990 (as amended) (England, Wales and Scotland). o Litter (Northern Ireland) Order 1994 (as amended). o Clean Neighbourhoods and Environment Act 2005 (England and Wales). o Code of Practice on Litter and Refuse (Eng- land) 2007. o Clean Neighbourhoods and Environment Act (Northern Ireland) 2011. o Code of Practice on Litter and Refuse (Scotland) 2006. 2. Is there any policy at national level addressing plastic production and use that impacts the oceans?", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "55bf5e57-a3ac-466f-b574-acd1d7f00707": {"__data__": {"id_": "55bf5e57-a3ac-466f-b574-acd1d7f00707", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/national-marine-plastic-litter-policies-eu-member-states", "Author": "Intern